<topic id="opening-document-from-cli">
  <title>Opening a Document at a Specific Location Using a Command-Line Interface</title>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <keywords>
        <indexterm>Open file at specific location</indexterm>
      </keywords>
    </metadata>
  </prolog>
  <body>
    <p><ph keyref="product"/> offers support for opening a file at a specific position using a
      command-line interface to transmit parameters to the <ph keyref="product"/> application
      launching script file (<ph product="editor"
          ><filepath>oxygen.bat</filepath>/<filepath>oxygen.sh</filepath></ph>
      <ph product="author"
          ><filepath>oxygenAuthor.bat</filepath>/<filepath>oxygenAuthor.sh</filepath></ph>
      <ph product="developer"
          ><filepath>oxygenDeveloper.bat</filepath>/<filepath>oxygenDeveloper.sh</filepath></ph>
      <ph product="svnClient"
          ><filepath>syncroSVNClient.bat</filepath>/<filepath>syncroSVNClient.sh</filepath></ph>).
      The following methods are available, depending on how you identify the position that is needed:<ol>
        <li>
          <p><u><b>Specific position values (line and column number, or character
            offset)</b></u></p>
          <p><ph keyref="product"/> supports the following position parameters:<ul>
              <li><b>line</b> - The line number.</li>
              <li><b>column</b> - The column number (has meaning if the <codeph>line</codeph>
                parameter is also defined).</li>
              <li><b>char</b> - The character offset.</li>
            </ul></p>
          <p><b>Examples for Windows:</b></p>
          <p>The following examples show how you can open an XML document in <ph keyref="product"/>
            from a Windows command-line
            interface:<codeblock outputclass="language-ini" product="editor">oxygen.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#line=4
oxygen.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#line=4column=5
oxygen.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#line=4;column=5
oxygen.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#char=334</codeblock><codeblock outputclass="language-ini" product="author">author.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#line=4
author.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#line=4column=5
author.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#line=4;column=5
author.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#char=334</codeblock><codeblock outputclass="language-ini" product="developer">developer.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#line=4
developer.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#line=4column=5
developer.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#line=4;column=5
developer.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#char=334</codeblock></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><u><b>Simplified XPath index path</b></u></p>
          <p><ph keyref="product"/> will open an XML file and select one of its elements identified
            by a simplified XPath index path. For example, an index path of the form 1/5/7
            identifies the seventh child of the fifth child of the root element. <note
              type="restriction"><ph keyref="product"/> will display a selection that starts with
              the first character of the content of the identified element and spans until the end
              of the line.</note></p>
          <p><b>Examples for Windows:</b></p>
          <p>The following example shows how you can open an XML document in <ph keyref="product"/>
            and select the third child of the root element using a Windows command-line
            interface:<codeblock outputclass="language-ini" product="editor">oxygen.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#element(1/3)</codeblock><codeblock outputclass="language-ini" product="author">author.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#element(1/3)</codeblock><codeblock outputclass="language-ini" product="developer">developer.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#element(1/3)</codeblock></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><u><b>Anchors identified by ID attribute values</b></u></p>
          <p><ph keyref="product"/> will open an XML file and select the element whose
              <xmlatt>id</xmlatt> attribute value is an exact match of the <xref
              keyref="glossentry_anchor"><term>anchor</term></xref> attached to a command-line
            instruction.</p>
          <p><b>Examples for Windows:</b></p>
          <p>The following example shows how you can open an XML document in <ph keyref="product"/>
            and select the element that has the <xmlatt>id</xmlatt> set to <codeph>titleID</codeph>
            using a Windows command-line
            interface:<codeblock outputclass="language-ini" product="editor">oxygen.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#titleID</codeblock><codeblock outputclass="language-ini" product="author">author.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#titleID</codeblock><codeblock outputclass="language-ini" product="developer">developer.bat  file:samples/personal.xml#titleID</codeblock></p>
        </li>
      </ol></p>
  </body>
